<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB75BFFA0C56ECDA33B02FA4C" blockId="1.[264,1077,1457,1480]" box="[264,1077,1457,1480]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<typeStatus id="5489885CB75BFFA0C56ECDA33E0AFA4C" box="[264,317,1457,1480]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Type</typeStatus>
species: 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB75BFFA0C5F9CDA33C34FA4C" authority="Lucas, 1857" authorityName="Lucas" authorityYear="1857" box="[415,771,1457,1480]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brasiliensis">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB75BFFA0C5F9CDA33D4DFA4C" box="[415,634,1457,1480]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Plateros brasiliensis</emphasis>
Lucas, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B75BFFA0C6A8CDA33C34FA4C" box="[718,771,1457,1480]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="1857.0">1857</number>
</taxonomicName>
(by subsequent designation)
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3286575B75BFFA0C56ECDE03D8CF8CF" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB75BFFA0C56ECDE03EFFF92F" blockId="1.[264,1324,1521,1867]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB75BFFA0C56ECDE03E48F98F" box="[264,383,1522,1547]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Diagnosis</emphasis>
. Antennomere 
<number id="3DFA24D9B75BFFA0C652CDE33D74F98F" box="[564,579,1521,1547]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="3.0">3</number>
broader and at least slightly longer than antennomere 
<number id="3DFA24D9B75BFFA0C0D8CDE33BF8F98F" box="[1214,1231,1521,1547]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="2.0">2</number>
, pronotum without carinae, median longitudinal line channelled basally, forming minute areola at posterior margin, each elytron with 
<number id="3DFA24D9B75BFFA0C6DDCE533DFDF9DF" box="[699,714,1601,1627]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2" value="9.0">9</number>
weak longitudinal costae connected by transverse costae, male genitalia without paramerae, ovipositor short, length of valvifers similar to those of coxites.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB75BFFA0C55ECEA83D8CF8CF" blockId="1.[264,1324,1521,1867]" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB75BFFA0C55ECEA83D28F957" box="[312,543,1722,1747]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="2">Sexual dimorphism</emphasis>
. Males and females differ mostly in the relative size of eyes, females having almost regularly eyes much smaller than interocular distance. If male antennae are serrate or flabellate, then female antennae are much slenderer, without or with minute antennomeral processes.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3286575B758FFA3C55EC90E3B76F92A" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB758FFA3C55EC90E3CADFE02" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C55EC90E3EF0FEB1" box="[312,455,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Distribution</emphasis>
. Worldwide distributed genus, known from all zoogeographical regions and many oceanic islands, absent in 
<collectingCountry id="F325766EB758FFA3C6AEC9563C5FFEDA" box="[712,872,324,350]" name="New Zealand" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">New Zealand</collectingCountry>
and Hawaii. The highest diversity is known from tropical rain forests of the Oriental Region.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB758FFA3C55EC9863B1EFD1A" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C55EC9863EA1FE29" box="[312,406,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Ecology</emphasis>
. The Sulawesi 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C629C9863D86FE29" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[591,689,404,429]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C629C9863D86FE29" box="[591,689,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species were collected in the lower mountain forests in the west Toraja region (Mamasa valley) and on the northern slope of the Lompobatang massif in the southernmost tip of Sulawesi (elevations 
<quantity id="4CCA9B1BB758FFA3C7F2C9F63B05FE7A" box="[916,1074,484,510]" metricMagnitude="3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.45" metricValueMax="1.8" metricValueMin="1.1" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" unit="m" value="1450.0" valueMax="1800.0" valueMin="1100.0">1100­1800 m</quantity>
a. s. l.). Adults were slowly moving or sitting on leaves of shrubs and trees of the lower forest canopy stratum. They were only seldom flying during day light and usually were not disturbed even by shaking branches. Larvae of Sulawesi 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C6B4CA4E3C02FDF1" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[722,821,604,629]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C6B4CA4E3C02FDF1" box="[722,821,604,629]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are unknown, but the development in rotting wood is expected as in relative species in neighbouring regions.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB758FFA3C55ECABE3BD8FB72" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Lycids are protected from predators by the presence of several odour and bitter compounds (
<bibRefCitation id="EFA34B0FB758FFA3C508CAC63D48FD6A" author="Moore, B. P. &amp; Brown, W. V." box="[366,639,724,750]" firstAuthor="Moore" journalOrPublisher="Insect Biochemistry" pageId="2" pageNumber="12" pagination="493 - 499" part="15" refId="ref6387" refString="Moore, B. P. &amp; Brown, W. V. (1981) Identification of warning odour components, bitter principles and antifeedants in an aposematic beetle - Metriorrhynchus rhipidium (Coleoptera: Lycidae). Insect Biochemistry, 15, 493 - 499." title="Identification of warning odour components, bitter principles and antifeedants in an aposematic beetle - Metriorrhynchus rhipidium (Coleoptera: Lycidae)" type="journal article" year="1981">
Moore &amp; Brown 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C627CAC63D48FD6A" box="[577,639,724,750]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1981.0">1981</number>
</bibRefCitation>
), and therefore they have a very strong tendency to form mimicry complexes. Unlike Sulawesi species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C737CAEE3C84FC91" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[849,947,764,789]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C737CAEE3C84FC91" box="[849,947,764,789]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from other regions are often brightly coloured and their body is often wider. The Sulawesi species can be divided in two groups considering general appearance. 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C77FCB5E3CD7FCE1" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1933" box="[793,992,844,869]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavidus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C77FCB5E3CD7FCE1" box="[793,992,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros flavidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C796CB5E3B5BFCE1" box="[1008,1132,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. t o l i e n s i s</emphasis>
nom. n., and 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C173CB5E3E0AFC09" authority="Tvardik &amp; Bocak, 2001" authorityName="Tvardik &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2001" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lalui" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C173CB5E3A13FCE1" box="[1301,1316,844,869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P</emphasis>
. 
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C56ECB663E0AFC09" box="[264,317,884,909]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">lalui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2755797B758FFA3C523CB663EB4FC0A" box="[325,387,884,910]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are brightly yellow coloured and their body is slightly wider. They remind unrelated genera 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C5C6CB8E3DF1FC32" authority="Pic, 1930" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1930" box="[416,710,924,950]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Microtrichalus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C5C6CB8E3D78FC31" box="[416,591,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Microtrichalus</emphasis>
Pic, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C6EDCB8E3DF1FC32" box="[651,710,924,950]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1930.0">1930</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C6B0CB8E3C80FC32" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[726,951,924,950]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Metriorrhynchinae">Metriorrhynchinae</taxonomicName>
, Trichalini), 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C029CB8E3E74FC5A" authority="Pic, 1926" authorityName="Pic" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Cautiromimus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C029CB8E3BC1FC31" box="[1103,1270,924,949]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Cautiromimus</emphasis>
Pic, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C56ECBD63E74FC5A" box="[264,323,964,990]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1926.0">1926</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C537CBD63D15FC5A" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[337,546,964,990]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Metriorrhynchini">Metriorrhynchini</taxonomicName>
), and undescribed genus of Lyropaeini (
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C794CBD63BB8FC5A" authorityName="Leng &amp; Mutchler" authorityYear="1922" box="[1010,1167,964,990]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Leptolycinae">Leptolycinae</taxonomicName>
) occurring in the same area. The second group is characterised by the slender, black body. They remind in general appearance several syntopically occurring 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C7E7CC063B82FBAA" authority="Bocak, 1999" authorityName="Bocak" authorityYear="1999" box="[897,1205,1044,1070]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Wakarumbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C7E7CC063B24FBA9" box="[897,1043,1044,1069]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Wakarumbia</emphasis>
Bocak, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C01CCC063B82FBAA" box="[1146,1205,1044,1070]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1999.0">1999</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C0A0CC063EBAFBD2" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Metriorrhynchinae">Metriorrhynchinae</taxonomicName>
, Hemiconderina), 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C612CC2E3CEEFBD2" authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[628,985,1084,1110]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C612CC2E3DC7FBD1" box="[628,752,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Xylobanus</emphasis>
Waterhouse, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C7FACC2E3CEEFBD2" box="[924,985,1084,1110]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1879.0">1879</number>
</taxonomicName>
, and 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C043CC2E3E74FBFA" authority="Waterhouse, 1879" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Broxylus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C043CC2E3BBBFBD1" box="[1061,1164,1084,1109]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Broxylus</emphasis>
Waterhouse, 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C56ECC763E74FBFA" box="[264,323,1124,1150]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="1879.0">1879</number>
</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C533CC763D11FBFA" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1926" box="[341,550,1124,1150]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Metriorrhynchini">Metriorrhynchini</taxonomicName>
). The silver pubescence well developed in most black Sulawesi 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C56ECC9E3E5DFB21" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[264,362,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C56ECC9E3E5DFB21" box="[264,362,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is similar to those in several species of 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C702CC9E3CC1FB21" authorityName="Bocak" authorityYear="1999" box="[868,1014,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Wakarumbia" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Metazoa" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C702CC9E3CC1FB21" box="[868,1014,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Wakarumbia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C05DCC9E3B80FB21" authorityName="Waterhouse" authorityYear="1879" box="[1083,1207,1164,1189]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Xylobanus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C05DCC9E3B80FB21" box="[1083,1207,1164,1189]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Xylobanus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
from the same area. Such pubescence has not been found in lycids from other regions and its coevolution in unrelated groups of lycids shows possible selective pressure from predators.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB758FFA3C55FCD163B76F92A" blockId="2.[264,1324,284,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C55FCD163D46FA99" box="[313,625,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Species level relationships</emphasis>
. The Sulawesi 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C74CCD163CBAFA99" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[810,909,1284,1309]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C74CCD163CBAFA99" box="[810,909,1284,1309]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
