(
<figureCitation id="13092A7BB758FFA3C62ECEF63DE7F97A" box="[584,720,1764,1790]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 27. 11 ­ 13" captionStartId="5.[264,383,1721,1745]" captionTargetBox="[348,1240,494,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[343,1242,494,1704]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 27. 11 ­ 13: Male genitalia. 11: Plateros rubromamasensis sp. n.; 12 ­ 13: P. lalui sp. n.; 14 ­ 19: Male pronota. 14: P. kalamensis sp. n.; 15: P. mamasensis sp. n.; 16: P. milenae sp. n.; 17: P. orobuensis sp. n.; 18: P. rubromamasensis sp. n.; 19: P. tanatorajensis sp. n.; 20: Female antenna. 20: P. flavidus Kleine, 1933; 21 ­ 27: Male antennae. 21: P. kalamensis sp. n.; 22: P. lalui sp. n.; 23: P. mamasensis sp. n.; 24: P. milenae sp. n.; 25: P. orobuensis sp. n.; 26: P. rubromamasensis sp. n.; 27: P. tanatorajensis sp. n. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155512/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figs 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C6E1CEF63DE7F97A" box="[647,720,1764,1790]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="23.0" valueMax="25.0" valueMin="21.0">21­25</number>
</figureCitation>
). Their male genitalia are characteristic in a very slender phallus and membranous internal sac (
<figureCitation id="13092A7BB758FFA3C74ECF1E3CAAF8A2" box="[808,925,1804,1830]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 ­ 10" captionStartId="4.[264,383,1831,1855]" captionTargetBox="[355,1246,605,1809]" captionTargetId="figure@4.[352,1252,603,1813]" captionText="FIGURES 1 ­ 10: Male genitalia. 1 ­ 2: Plateros kalamensis sp. n.; 3 ­ 4: P. m a m a s e n s i s sp. n.; 5 ­ 6: P. milenae sp. n.; 7 ­ 8: P. orobuensis sp. n.; 9 ­ 10: P. tanatorajensis sp. n. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155511/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Figs 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C702CF1E3CAAF8A2" box="[868,925,1804,1830]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="8.5" valueMax="10.0" valueMin="7.0">7­10</number>
</figureCitation>
). The similar shape of the phallus is found in 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB758FFA3C5EBCF263D65F8C9" authority="Tvardik &amp; Bocak, 2001" authorityName="Tvardik &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2001" box="[397,594,1844,1869]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tanatorajensis" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB758FFA3C5EBCF263D65F8C9" box="[397,594,1844,1869]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">P. tanatorajensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2755797B758FFA3C63FCF263DADF8CA" box="[601,666,1844,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, which differs in acutely serrate antennae (
<figureCitation id="13092A7BB758FFA3C0F6CF263BDFF8CA" box="[1168,1256,1844,1870]" captionStart="FIGURES 11 ­ 27. 11 ­ 13" captionStartId="5.[264,383,1721,1745]" captionTargetBox="[348,1240,494,1701]" captionTargetId="figure@5.[343,1242,494,1704]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11 ­ 27. 11 ­ 13: Male genitalia. 11: Plateros rubromamasensis sp. n.; 12 ­ 13: P. lalui sp. n.; 14 ­ 19: Male pronota. 14: P. kalamensis sp. n.; 15: P. mamasensis sp. n.; 16: P. milenae sp. n.; 17: P. orobuensis sp. n.; 18: P. rubromamasensis sp. n.; 19: P. tanatorajensis sp. n.; 20: Female antenna. 20: P. flavidus Kleine, 1933; 21 ­ 27: Male antennae. 21: P. kalamensis sp. n.; 22: P. lalui sp. n.; 23: P. mamasensis sp. n.; 24: P. milenae sp. n.; 25: P. orobuensis sp. n.; 26: P. rubromamasensis sp. n.; 27: P. tanatorajensis sp. n. Scale 0.5 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/155512/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="3">
Fig. 
<number id="3DFA24D9B758FFA3C0A1CF263BDFF8CA" box="[1223,1256,1844,1870]" pageId="2" pageNumber="3" value="27.0">27</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8D36FEB759FFA2C55EC90E3B2FFE7A" blockId="3.[264,1324,284,510]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">
The males of 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB759FFA2C5BFC90E3D64FEB1" authorityName="Kleine" authorityYear="1933" box="[473,595,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavidus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB759FFA2C5BFC90E3D64FEB1" box="[473,595,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. flavidus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB759FFA2C6EBC90E3C3BFEB1" authorityName="Tvardik &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2001" box="[653,780,284,309]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="toliensis" status="nom. n.">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB759FFA2C6EBC90E3C3BFEB1" box="[653,780,284,309]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. toliensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2755797B759FFA2C775C90E3C5BFEB2" box="[787,876,284,310]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">nom. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
are unknown and therefore their relationships with newly described species remain unclear. They differ in serrate female antennae from dark coloured species and from 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB759FFA2C771C97E3C58FE01" authority="Tvardik &amp; Bocak, 2001" authorityName="Tvardik &amp; Bocak" authorityYear="2001" box="[791,879,364,389]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lalui" status="sp. n.">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB759FFA2C771C97E3C58FE01" box="[791,879,364,389]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">P. lalui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A2755797B759FFA2C71DC97E3CF5FE02" box="[891,962,364,390]" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" rank="species">sp. n.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, which is the closest species considering body shape and colouration. The serrate female antennae are usually present in 
<taxonomicName id="4C324D7DB759FFA2C541C9AE3EBDFE51" authorityName="Bourgeois" authorityYear="1879" box="[295,394,444,469]" class="Insecta" family="Lycidae" genus="Plateros" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF,CoL" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="4" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B946EAECB759FFA2C541C9AE3EBDFE51" box="[295,394,444,469]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="4">Plateros</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species with flabellate male antennae. Males are necessary for the clarification of the relationships and for accurate identification of these species.
</paragraph>
